text_answer.content:
Key Details 3 could be C or D. C is obviously the intended answer (and the easier one to understand), but passage 1 clearly talks about how wind turbines affect birds and wildlife while passage 2 suggests that the wildlife adapted to the wind turbine.

Still not a huge fan of one or two sources, but the last unit was especially bad about its accuracy on facts, and I had to default to including false or unverifiable information if there were less than three sources listed. I'll give this unit a pass on this front until I have reason to change my mind.

text_answer.content:
This passage's shelf life has already expired. Easy fix, though. Change 'the 2024 Paris Paralympics will feature' to 'the 2024 Paris Paralympic featured' and it'll be fine.
Question 5 is a fantastic inference, though the wording is a little off.  I'd probably cut 'and necessity' and just focus on the respect.

I think I get what the Mind Map is asking for, but I had to look at the answer key to be confident. I think it's the 'focusing on facts vs. storytelling elements, which feels overly specific for what I believe this is trying to get students to do. Unless there's a specific thing you're trying to get out of this version of the Mind Map, I don't see why it needs to be there. If there is something specific you're trying to accomplish, then it's unclear.

text_answer.content:
Soft no on appropriateness. There's nothing wrong, per se, but these are a pretty intense pair of essays. The non-fiction passage is basically fine (though that last sentence if funny...), but the fiction passage might be a little graphic for the tutoring environment. Flagging so a decision can be made.
Question 1's answer is the only one with three items.
Question 2 is a bit on the easy side.
Question 3's answer is the only one with two items.
Question 4 isn't an inference. Passage 2: "questioning the humanity of those who valued profit over children's lives." Passage 1 doesn't say it outright, but "These young laborers..." in paragraph 2 and the last sentence are pretty close.
Question 5 is also not an inference, since it's explicitly stated in the passage.

text_answer.content:
The fiction passage is a bit easy.
Question 1's answer is the only one that isn't used in modern legal trials.
Question 2 is... eh. There's so much going on that A, B, and D are automatically valid. C and E can be eliminated.

Not a huge fan of how the Mind Map separates the passages. The overall intention should be to have the student's work highlight the similarities and differences - especially since the second passage included the fact about the "afflicted" girls  which wasn't really discussed in the first passage.
In my mind, a better comparison would be to look at how the legal proceedings described in the passage in 1692 compare to a more modern process - though admittedly even then the second passage has no examination of the modern process.

text_answer.content: Some language which promotes mystification/alienation of indigenous peoples. "Indomitable spirit of [America's] frontier pioneers" contrasted with "savage beauty" and the faceless whooping assault of the Paiute antagonists in the fiction passage has a way of ennobling frontiersmen while denigrating and dehumanizing natives. Reverence can be paid to the accomplishments of the Pony Express riders and acknowledgement can be made of the conflict between US citizens and indigenous people without exoticizing native populations.
